# Day 5 – Rocket Competition & Conservation Expo

## Activities
- Competed in the water rocket launch competition, where my rocket reached a height of **77 feet**.
- Ate lunch with the camp and visited the NC State Bookstore before getting ice cream.
- Worked with my group to create our final Expo project.
- Chose to develop an **animal conservation plan** focused on **sea turtles** and **giant pandas**, two endangered species.
- Used AI responsibly to research information, organize ideas, and improve our conservation plan.
- Explained how AI assisted our project and highlighted the benefits of using AI ethically in real-world situations.
- Presented our finished project during the gallery walk, where parents and visitors viewed everyone's work and learned about each group's project.

## What I Learned
Today, I learned that engineering projects often involve testing, improving, and learning from results, as demonstrated during the rocket competition. I also learned more about endangered species and the challenges that sea turtles and giant pandas face in the wild.
While creating our conservation plan, I discovered how AI can be a valuable tool for brainstorming ideas, organizing research, and improving communication when it is used responsibly. 
The gallery walk also showed me the importance of presenting ideas clearly and explaining both the scientific concepts and the role AI played in our project.

## Favorite Part
My favorite part of the day was presenting our conservation project during the gallery walk. It was rewarding to share what my group had created with our parents and see everyone's different ideas. 
I also enjoyed the rocket competition because it was exciting to watch my rocket fly **77 feet** after applying what I had learned earlier in the week. Finishing the camp by combining teamwork, creativity, science, and AI made it a memorable experience.
